occurrences.line_text: That as the Sunny beames do glaunce and glide
In secret shadow from the sunny ray,
Like Phoebus face adornd with sunny rayes,
The sunny beames, which on the billowes bet,
As doth the lilly fresh before the sunny ray.
But all the day before the sunny rayes
And raught vnto her heeles; like sunny beames,
Fresh shadowes, fit to shroud from sunny ray;
That feeles the warmth of sunny beames reflection,
That flakes of fire, bright as the sunny ray,
Whose skirts were bordred with bright sunny beams,
Her stately towres, and buildings sunny sheene;
Did shew it selfe in sunny beames bedight,
And made a sunshine in the shadie place;
And gins to spread his leafe before the faire sunshine.
Then in the sunshine of her countenance cleare
At flashing beames of that sunshiny shield,
And her sunshynie helmet soone vnlaced,
As they are wont in faire sunshynie weather,
And glorious light of her sunshyny face
Death and despeyre did many thereof sup,
For nought was giuen them to sup or dyne,
Such superfluities they would despise,
Vaine feasts, and idle superfluity:
And belcheth forth his superfluity,
And euer as superfluous flesh did rot
The image of superfluous riotize,
Markes which do byte their hasty supper best;
To thinke, how supper did them long awaite.
Supper was shortly dight and downe they sat,
Yet tried did adore. Supper was dight;
And rest himselfe, till supper time befell.
And supper readie dight, they to it fell
To ouerthrow, but to supplant by slight.
The flesh therewith she suppled and did steepe,
Still holding vp her suppliant hands on hye,
But he her suppliant hands, those hands of gold,
Whose glorie is to aide all suppliants pore,
To suppliants, through frayltie which offend.
Faire Sir, said then the Palmer suppliaunt,
And wants supplide. And then againe abroad
For Aruirage his brothers place supplide,
Doubly supplide, in spousall, and dominion.
For twise foure hundreth yeares shalbe supplide,
Supplide her sobbing breaches with sad complement.
She in my stead supplide his bestiall desire.
This hand may helpe, or succour ought supplie,
It were, or other new supplied knight.
It strength to me supplies, & chears my dulled spright.
He did supply their want, and gaue them euer free.
That money can thy wantes at will supply?
His sonne Riuallo his dead roome did supply,
Did natiue courage vnto him supply,
That whilest his breath did strength to him supply,
Vnfit faire Ladies seruice to supply;
And with vaine hope his spirits faint supply,
And with thy punishment his penance shalt supply.
For well she wist this knight came, succour to supply.
Be lacke of children, to supply your place,
And each sought to supply the office of her page.
To haue supplyde the first, and paide the vsury.
Art playing second natures part, supplyed it.
An huge eternall Chaos, which supplyes
Which doe the temple of the Gods support,
She did support, and Impotence her name:
With which his daughter doth him still support;
She doth support, and strongly beateth downe
Or through support of count'nance proud and hault
So as it was vnable to support
Was holpen vp, who him supported standing neare.
Called Fidess', and so supposd to bee;
Supposd to be. They do arriue anone,
(As they supposd) but her had to her liking left.
And many a one suppos'd to be a mayd:
Eftsoones supposed him a person meet,
Which he supposed donne to Florimell,
As raging flames who striueth to suppresse.
Teach him the weake to strengthen, & the stro[n]g suppresse.
Their arbers spoyle, their Cabinets suppresse,
Shall well defend, and Saxons powre suppresse,
Her hard pursewd, and sought for to suppresse;
And all men busie to suppresse the flame,
And did the rest with grieuous sighes suppresse,
But faithfull friendship doth them both suppresse,
I will suppresse, that they no more may raine;
So meaning to suppresse both forged guile,
In vaine he seeketh others to suppresse,
Did him suppresse, and forcibly subdew;
That at the last suppressing fury mad,
But still suppressing gan of her inquire,
Vnder his Lordly foot him proudly hath supprest.
Euen he it was, that earst would haue supprest
But both alike, when death hath both supprest,
Hath long bene vnderkept, and downe supprest,
Mote easie be supprest with little thing:
Of doughty Calidore, supprest and tamed,
Of which he supt so oft, that on his seat
Least they their finnes should bruze, and surbate sore
Espye a traueiler with feet surbet,
He mote surcease his suit, and lose the hope
As that in stead of praying them surcease,
Causd all her people to surcease from fight,
Remoued is, th'effect surceaseth still.
Ne ought the more their mightie strokes surceasse,
And would them faine from battell to surceasse,
Ne secretly from thought of fell reuenge surceasse.
He would surceasse, but him, where so he were, would seeke.
Them yielded readie passage, and their rage surceast.
Were it not good that wrong were then surceast,
Had long surceast, she bad to open bold,
Surcharg'd with wine, were heedlesse and ill hedded.
Was fled to hell, surcharg'd with spoile and theft.
Foure charged two, and two surcharged one;
Strangle her, else she sure will strangle thee.
Fly to your faith for succour and sure ayde:
Nothing is sure, that growes on earthly ground:
For dearely sure her loue was to me bent,
Prince Arthur gaue a boxe of Diamond sure,
And am I now in safetie sure (quoth he)
Are written sure, and haue their certaine date.
Dead was it sure, as sure as death in deed,
Dead was it sure, as sure as death in deed,
Where she enioyes sure peace for euermore,
That shall I shew (said he) as sure, as hound
Else be ye sure he dearely shall abyde,
And by the knighthood, which they sure had sworne,
Thus said; Old man, great sure shalbe thy meed,
For who can tell (and sure I feare it ill)
And sure he was a man of mickle might,
Great glory and gay spoile sure hast thou got,
Great mercy sure, for to enlarge a thrall,
For sure it would deceiue thy labour, and thy might.
How euer, sure I rew his pitteous plight.
And to him said, Now felon sure I read,
Soone it must turne to earth; no earthly thing is sure.
What euer be the cause, it sure beseemes you ill.
Is setled there in sure establishment;
Then thought the Prince all perill sure was past,
Loue haue I sure, (quoth she) but Lady none;
But if that loue it be, as sure I read
Great pittie sure, that ye be so forlorne
So sure and swiftly, through his perfect scent,
And how she might be sure, that I would neuer swerue.
Or ill they seemed sure auizd to bee,
That sure I weene, the hardest hart of stone,
Who thereby deeming sure the thing as donne,
To turne his steede about, or sure he should be ded.
Her certaine losse, if not her sure decay:
For sure a foole I do him firmely hold,
From Limbo lake him late escaped sure would say.
Be sure, that nought may saue thee from to dy,
Misdeeming sure that her those flames did burne;
For sure the fayrest Florimell him seemed,
For vertue is the band, that bindeth harts most sure.
The soule had sure out of his bodie riued,
Yet dead he was not, yet he sure did die,
Which Triamond perceiuing, weened sure
And sure had it not happily found rest
They weened sure the warre was at an end,
Who[m] sure he weend, that he some wher tofore had eide.
Him needeth sure a golden pen I weene,
Some gladfull newes and sure intelligence,
And of vs three to morrow he will sure eate one.
A foule and loathly creature sure in sight,
Whose noble kind at first was sure of heauenly seed.
And sure had not his massie yron mace
But cause of feare sure had she none at all
The which I found sure lockt and chained fast.
But sooth it was not sure for womanish shame,
For sure she weend it was some one of those,
And sayd, Now sure this doubtfull causes right
That sure they ween'd she was escapt away:
We are not sure they would so long remaine:
Now sure (said he) and by the faith that I
Vppon her person for her sure defence,
But with sweet loue and sure beneuolence,
Did with sure promise of her good indeuour,
Vnworthy sure (quoth he) of better day,
Which she would sure performe, betide her wele or wo.
For sure he weend, that this his present guest
For else he sure had left not one aliue,
That one sure stroke he might vnto him reach,
Yet in that wretched semblant, she did sure
This well I wote, that sure she is as great,
And sure he had her slaine, had she not turnd her way.
To whom he thus; She liueth sure and sound;
Then thus replide; Now sure and by my life,
But sure to me her faith she first did plight,
Of colour rustie browne, but sure and strong;
She deem'd him sure to haue bene dead on ground,
That sure he deem'd him borne of noble race.
Faire was the Ladie sure, that mote content
Now sure (then said Sir Calidore) and right
That sure he weend him borne of noble blood,
In hope he sure would proue a doughtie knight:
Him they did deeme, as sure to them he seemed,
Amongst so many foes, whom sure he thought
And sayd; Now sure ye well haue earn'd your meed,
Thought sure haue pownded him to powder soft,
And sure I weene, had not the Ladies cry
And soothly sure she was full fayre of face,
Thought sure t'auenge his grudge, & worke his foe great shame.
His dearest ioynt he sure had broken quight.
But what so sure she was, she worthy was,
Sayd Calidore ; Now sure it yrketh mee,
That here on earth is no sure happinesse,
That yond same is your daughter sure, which yet doth liue.
For may I boldly say, he surely is
Would surely deeme it to be yuie trew:
From rash reuenge, she had him surely slaine,
He surely dempt, himselfe he thought depriued
That who so then her saw, would surely say,
For dead, I surely doubt, thou maist aread
Extremely mad the man I surely deeme,
Had ye them seene, ye would haue surely thought,
His will she feard; for him she surely thought
So did they surely during all their dayes,
As if the conquest his he surely wist.
Some newborne wight ye would him surely weene:
That she should surely beare the bell away,
And bad him rise, or surely he should die.
Such thraldome or such freedome let it surely be.
And said, that surely Florimell it was,
That all on fire ye would her surely weene.
And therefore ment him surely to haue slaine.
More happie mother would her surely weene,
He had him surely clouen quite in twaine.
Which may a Knight assure, had surely bound,
That surely is that Beast (saide Calidore)
Ne wote I surely, whether her he yet haue fond.
Ne surely thus vnarm'd I likely were;
Or surely borne of some Heroicke sead,
Glad would I surely be, thou courteous Squire,
She made him thinke it surely was his owne,
Where I had surely long ere this bene dead,
Else had he surely there bene slaine, or fowlyshent.
Vnder that villaines club, then surely thought
Surely my sonne (then answer'd he againe)
He thus replyde; Now surely syre, I find,
Good will and fauour. So it surely wrought
Matched with equall yeares, do surely prieue
And often to him calling, to take surer hould.
Tooke surer hould, and from his horses backe
And eke of surest steele, that may be found,
The surest signe, whereby ye may her know,
Of surest yron, made with many a lincke;
Surfeat, misdiet, and vnthriftie wast,
(This Tryphon is the seagods surgeon hight)
That quite they seem'd past helpe of surgery,
And streight they saw the raging surges reard
Tho hauing vewd a while the surges hore,
To rule his tides, and surges to vprere,
Doth frie with fome aboue the surges hore.
And she her selfe in stormie surges tost;
From surging gulf two monsters straight were brought,
The surging waters like a mountaine rise,
The surging seas, when they do sorest rage,
Prouokt with VVrath, and Enuies false surmise,
The more to be true Florimell he did surmize.
By which all earthly Princes she doth farre surmount.
For though their numbers do much more surmount,
No lesse then perfect gold surmounts the meanest brasse.
For Rhodoricke, whose surname shalbe Great,
To proue her surname true, that she imposed has.
He all his Peeres in beautie did surpas,
For this great Citie that does far surpas,
So much her malice did her might surpas,
And did in strength most sorts of men surpas,
Whose beauty doth her bounty far surpasse,
So he surpassed his sex masculine,
The worke of heauens will surpasseth humaine thought.
Farre passing that, which by surpassing skill
But him in strength and skill the Prince surpast,
And looke what surplus did of each remaine,
Take what thou please of all this surplusage;
Surprisd her sense: she therewith well apayd,
He was surprisd, and buried vnder beare,
He was vnwares surprisd in subtile bands
Here wonnes Acrasia, whom we must surprise,
Now singing sweetly, to surprise her sprights,
And he too simple euer to surprise
There heauie sleepe the eye-lids did surprise
Vnwares surprised, and with mightie mall
Had them surprised. At last auizing right,
Castles surprizd, great cities sackt and brent:
Yet now he was surpriz'd: for that false spright,
And traynes hauing surpriz'd, he fouly did to die.
Encountring fierce, him suddaine doth surprize,
Whylest time did offer meanes him sleeping to surprize.
Did runne at Pastorell, her to surprize:
She was asham'd to be so loose surprized,
Surprized was, and to Grantorto brought,
That hidden lyes vnwares him to surpryse?
Vile rancour to auoid, and cruell surquedrie.
With which he boasted in his surquedrie,
Transform'd to fish, for their bold surquedry,
Had them enraged with fell surquedry;
In their auenge, tread downe the victours surquedry.
And in their raging surquedry disdaynd,
Might wanting measure moueth surquedry.
At last ripe age bad him surrender late
She it surrendred, ne her selfe would lenger vex.
Till he surrendred Realme and life to fate.
And did suruay his goodly company:
Which it suruew'd, as hils doen lower ground;
Of natiue strength now, that he them suruiu'd.
Nor that sage Pylian syre, which did suruiue
That had not grace thee blest, thou shouldest not suruiue.
Yet after all, he victour did suruiue,
Of thine owne spirit, which doth in me suruiue,
Or is she thrall, or doth she not suruiue?
When she so faire a daughter saw suruiue,
Into his other brethren, that suruiued,
Suspect her truth: yet since no' vntruth he knew,
And walketh forth without suspect of crime:
Suspect her truth, and keepe continuall spy
And after them Dissemblance, and Suspect
Iealous suspect as true vntruely drad,
Without suspect of ill or daungers hidden dred.
And feeble hope hung all this while suspence,
And stood still mute, as one in great suspence,
Ouer the sea, suspended dreadfully,
And their true loues without suspition tell abrode.
Besides, that more suspition encreast,
Matter of doubt and dread suspitious,
For the rebuke, which she sustain'd that day,
That nought so wondrous puissance might sustaine;
That nothing might sustaine his furious forse;
In her loose lap, it softly to sustaine,
That neither could his mightie puissance sustaine.
Vnhable their encounter to sustaine;
And combrous conflict, which they did sustaine,
Next whom Morindus did the crowne sustaine,
That goodly frame from ruine to sustaine:
Nor bounds nor banks his headlong ruine may sustaine.
And doth himselfe with sorrow new sustaine,
When her weake feete could scarcely her sustaine,
They felt, could once sustaine the hideous stowre,
That neither could the others force sustaine;
For so great trauell, as you doe sustaine:
When as the Carle no longer could sustaine,
That yron heart it hardly could sustaine:
That neither could the others stroke sustaine,
An infant, weake a kingdome to sustaine,
And setting on his steede, her did sustaine
Did vse, his feeble body to sustaine;
Aread good sire, some counsell, that may vs sustaine.
Sith he likewise did wrong by him sustaine,
Rather then once his burden to sustaine:
Which that straunge knight for him sustained had,
Therefore on either side she was sustained
The massy roofe, and riches huge sustayne,
Who mightily that scepter did sustayne,
All Faery lond does peaceable sustene.
Then gan the Peoples cry and Commons sute,
To whom their sute they humbly did present,
With humble seruice, and with daily sute,
There as thou slepst in tender swadling band,
When heauie hammers on the wedge are swaid;
And to him cals, Rise rise vnhappy Swaine,
Whose fellowship seemd far vnfit for warlike swaine.
Like scattered Sheepe, whenas the Shepheards swaine
From yielding succour to that cursed Swaine,
How to take life from that dead-liuing swaine,
So deepe the deadly feare of that foule swaine
Now certes swaine (said he) such one I weene,
It was a goodly Swaine, and of great might,
Yet knight he was not, but a boastfull swaine,
There dwels he euer, miserable swaine,
Who seemd of riper yeares, then th'other Swaine,
On th'other side, full many a warlike swaine,
It was my lot to loue a gentle swaine,
That he whilome some gentle swaine had beene,
This louely swaine the Squire of low degree;
So whylome learnd that mighty Iewish swaine,
At length bespake; What meanes this, gentle swaine?
Then turning to that swaine, him well he knew
But sith we need good counsell (sayd the swaine)
Him to betray vnto a straunger swaine:
Not I so happy, answerd then that swaine,
So taking leaue of that same gentle swaine,
Like as whylome that strong Tirynthian swaine,
High Swale, vnquiet Nide, and troublous Skell;
And boast to swallow her in greedy graue;
More swift, then swallow sheres the liquid skie,
Which gaping wide, to swallow them aliue,
Threatning to swallow vp my fearefull life?
For he was swift as swallow in her flight,
With which he swallowd vp excessiue feast,
His mournefull plight, is swallowd vp vnwares,
He thought attonce him to haue swallowd quight,
Which hauing swallowd vp excessiuely,
Her to haue swallow'd vp, did helpe to saue her.
Vnwares the hidden hooke with baite I swallowed.
As swift as swallowes, on the waues they went,
In which he swam, and ranne to his redresse.
Then was he turnd into a snowy Swan,
He knocked fast, and often curst, and sware,
A thousand villeins round about them swarmd
Which through the world the[m] swarmd in euery part,
As when a swarme of Gnats at euentide
Sith now he is farre from his monstrous swarme,
He like a swarme of flyes them ouerthrew;
They round about him gan to swarme apace,
Who flocking round about them, as a swarme
Against the Picts, that swarmed ouer all,
And like a sort of Bees in clusters swarmed:
Like many swarmes of Bees assembled round,
That swarmes of damned soules to hell he sends:
That all the place with swarmes do ouerlay,
Which swarming all about his legs did crall,
Of swarming Bees, did cast him in a swowne:
Those spoilefull Picts, and swarming Easterlings,
So many theeues about him swarming are,
Vntill a nation straung, with visage swart,
Of swarth complexion, and of crabbed hew,
But to his starting steed, that swaru'd asyde,
For seeing it at hand, he swaru'd asyde,
But swaru'd aside, and there againe did stay;
Her stedfast eyes were bent, ne swarued other way.
Yet swarued not, but kept their forward way,
Who from his saddle swarued nought asyde,
With that she swaruing backe, her Iauelin bright
But swaruing from the marke, his Lords life did assure.
He swaruing with the force, within his flesh
For sore he swat, and running through that same
And swat, and chauf'd, and proued euery way:
The doubtfull ballaunce equally to sway,
Did fall to ground, and with his heauie sway
At last low stouping with vnweldie sway,
And both attonce their huge blowes downe did sway;
His poinant speare he thrust with puissant sway
The which diuiding with importune sway,
Like Noyes great flood, with their importune sway,
Madan was young, vnmeet the rule of sway,
The same he snatcht, and with exceeding sway
Whose circled waters rapt with whirling sway,
That women wont in warres to beare most sway,
Long time ye both in armes shall beare great sway,
And that, which more then all the rest may sway,
Serued a gentle Lady of great sway,
That fortune all in equall launce doth sway,
His mighty rage, and with imperious sway
That bore great sway in armes and chiualrie,
And heau'd his murdrous axe at him with mighty sway.
Strikes at an Heron with all his bodies sway,
When all vnwares he felt an hideous sway
And heauie sway, that hard vnto his crowne
In which these Squires true friendship more did sway,
The wide kingdome of loue with Lordly sway,
Or shew the sweat, with which thou diddest sway
Much was she moued with the mightie sway
That made him stagger with vncertaine sway,
But as she prest on him with heauy sway,
And wading through the waues with stedfast sway,
And borne great sway in armes amongst his peares:
The which descended with such dreadfull sway,
That downe he kept him with his scornefull sway,
Thy cursed hand so cruelly haue swayd
Yet oft the Briton kings against them strongly swayd.
The first and eldest, which that scepter swayd,
Here, there, and euery where about her swayd
To Therion, a loose vnruly swayne;
But nathemore would that courageous swayne
Some goodly swayne of honorable place,
But the fresh Swayne would not his leasure dwell,
Yet was that other swayne this elders syre,
To yeeld strong succour to that gentle swayne,
But th'Elfin swayne, that oft had seene like sight,
As then the guize was for each gentle swayne;
Faire gentle swayne, and yet as stout as fayre,
And fitteth most for noble swayne to know,
The fearefull swayne beholding death so nie,
That other swayne, like ashes deadly pale,
Now turne againe my teme thou iolly swayne,
Ne was there heard, ne was there shepheards swayne
That she did loue a stranger swayne then him more dere.
Emongst the shepheard swaynes, then wexeth wood & yond.
And eke the gentle shepheard swaynes, which sat
The lustie shepheard swaynes sate in a rout,
One day when as the shepheard swaynes together
And ye faire swayns, after your long turmoyle,
Stood still amaz'd, holding his idle sweard;
And at that instant reaching forth his sweard
Into the graue, and gan deuoutly sweare;
When Braggadocchio said, Once I did sweare,
Shall yield him selfe his liegeman, and sweare fealty.
I sweare, ere long shall dearely it repent;
Sweare she is yours, and stirre vp bloudie frayes,
Well know'st thou, whe[n] we friendship first did sweare,
All full of rage he gan to curse and sweare,
So ye will sweare my iudgement to abide.
Made them sweare fealty to Artegall.
So suffring him to rise, he made him sweare
There him he causd to kneele, and made to sweare
Of blame, as he did on his Knighthood sweare,
And fiercely drawing forth his blade, doth sweare,
In vaine the Pagan bannes, and sweares, and rayles,
And swearing faith to either on his blade,
Swearing, and banning most blasphemously,
